# Translation Content Guidelines

When working with translations and i18n content, follow these principles:

## Translation Quality

### Natural Language
- Write text that **appears to be originally written in that language**, not like a (literal) translation
- Adapt content to **cultural context** and local conventions
- Use **appropriate tone** for the target audience (professional but approachable)
- Maintain a **confident but not arrogant** tone across all languages - be convincing (overtuigend) without being boastful
- Ensure the tone **matches the portfolio's purpose** of attracting clients and showcasing expertise

### Consistency
- Maintain **consistent terminology** across all translations
- Use the same **technical terms** throughout (e.g., "Django REST Framework" stays the same)
- Keep **brand names and proper nouns** consistent across languages, with exceptions for official local names (e.g., "Delft University of Technology" / "Technische Universiteit Delft")

### Length and Formatting
- **Adapt text length** to fit UI constraints in each language
- Some languages are naturally longer/shorter - adjust accordingly
- Preserve **line breaks and formatting** where they serve a purpose
- Use **non-breaking spaces** (`\u00A0`) for proper text flow

## Content Adaptation

### Cultural Context
- **Localize examples** and references when appropriate
- Consider **cultural differences** in communication style
- Adapt **idioms and expressions** to natural equivalents

### Technical Content
- Keep **technical terms** consistent across languages
- Use **established translations** for common tech terms
- Maintain **code examples and URLs** unchanged

### Dynamic Content
- Preserve **numbered placeholders** (`<1>`, `<2>`) exactly as they appear
- Ensure **placeholder context** makes sense in each language
- Test **placeholder positioning** in different text lengths

## Language-Specific Formatting

### English
- Use **title case** in places where title case is normally used (headings, titles)
- Use **Oxford comma** in lists (e.g., "red, white, and blue")
- Use **em-dashes** (—) for emphasis and breaks

### Dutch, German, and Other Languages
- **Avoid em-dashes** — use language-appropriate punctuation instead
- Follow **local capitalization rules** (e.g., German nouns are capitalized, Dutch titles use sentence case)
- Use **language-appropriate comma rules** (no Oxford comma in Dutch/German)
- Use **informal address** for Dutch (je/jij) and **formal address** for French (vous) and German (Sie)

## Examples

### Good Translation Examples

**Natural Language:**
```json
// English
"developer_intro": "I design and build web tools that feel simple — but solve tough challenges behind the scenes."

// Dutch (natural, not literal)
"developer_intro": "Ik maak webtools die eenvoudig te gebruiken zijn – en complexe problemen oplossen."

// German (confident but not arrogant)
"developer_intro": "Ich entwickle Web-Tools, die einfach wirken – aber komplexe Herausforderungen im Hintergrund lösen."
```

**Cultural Adaptation:**
```json
// English
"hobbies": "Outside of work, I enjoy strolling in Efteling, a Dutch park with a unique enchanting charm."

// Dutch (local context)
"hobbies": "Buiten werk vertoef ik graag in de Efteling, speel ik Nintendo-spellen of leer ik vreemde talen."

// German (adapted for German audience)
"hobbies": "In meiner Freizeit genieße ich Spaziergänge im Efteling, einem niederländischen Park mit einzigartigem Charme."
```

**V/T Distinction:**
```json
// Dutch (informal - je/jij)
"contact": {
  "text": "Goede resultaten bereik je samen. Laten we ontdekken hoe we dat kunnen waarmaken."
}

// German (formal - Sie)
"contact": {
  "text": "Gute Ergebnisse erreicht man gemeinsam. Lassen Sie uns herausfinden, wie wir das gemeinsam möglich machen."
}

// French (formal - vous)
"contact": {
  "text": "De bons résultats s'obtiennent ensemble. Explorons comment nous pouvons y parvenir."
}
```

**Technical Consistency:**
```json
// Keep technical terms consistent across languages
"backend": {
  "drf": {
    "full": "Django REST Framework",  // Same in all languages
    "short": "Django REST Framew.",
    "shortest": "Django REST Fw."
  }
}
```

### What to Avoid

**Literal Translations:**
```json
// Original (English) → Bad (literal Dutch) → Good (natural Dutch)
"developer_intro": {
  "original": "I design and build web tools that feel simple — but solve tough challenges behind the scenes.",
  "bad": "Ik ontwerp en bouw webtools die eenvoudig voelen — maar moeilijke uitdagingen achter de schermen oplossen.",
  "good": "Ik maak webtools die eenvoudig te gebruiken zijn – en complexe problemen oplossen."
}

// Original (English) → Bad (literal German) → Good (natural German)
"project_description": {
  "original": "I built a website that runs very fast and can handle many users.",
  "bad": "Ich habe eine Website gebaut, die sehr schnell läuft und viele Benutzer handhaben kann.",
  "good": "Ich entwickelte eine hochperformante Website mit hoher Benutzerkapazität."
}

// Original (English) → Bad (literal French) → Good (natural French)
"about_me": {
  "original": "I am a passionate developer who loves creating amazing things.",
  "bad": "Je suis un développeur passionné qui aime créer des choses incroyables.",
  "good": "Développeur passionné, j'aime créer des solutions innovantes."
}

// Original (Dutch) → Bad (literal German) → Good (natural German)
"contact_text": {
  "original": "Goede resultaten bereik je samen. Laten we ontdekken hoe we dat kunnen waarmaken.",
  "bad": "Gute Ergebnisse erreichst du zusammen. Lass uns entdecken, wie wir das verwirklichen können.",
  "good": "Gute Ergebnisse erreicht man gemeinsam. Lassen Sie uns herausfinden, wie wir das gemeinsam möglich machen."
}

// Original (English) → Bad (literal French) → Good (natural French)
"contact_cta": {
  "original": "Let's talk about your next project.",
  "bad": "Parlons de votre prochain projet.",
  "good": "Parlons de votre prochain projet."
}

// Original (English) → Bad (literal German) → Good (natural German)
"skills_title": {
  "original": "Tools I Rock With",
  "bad": "Werkzeuge mit denen ich rocke",
  "good": "Tools die ich benutze"
}
```

**Inconsistent Tone:**
```json
// ❌ Bad - too formal for portfolio
"contact_button": "Veuillez me contacter"

// ✅ Good - confident but approachable
"contact_button": "Contact"
```

**Cultural Missteps:**
```json
// ❌ Bad - em-dash in Dutch
"developer_intro": "Ik maak webtools die eenvoudig zijn — en complexe problemen oplossen."

// ✅ Good - appropriate punctuation
"developer_intro": "Ik maak webtools die eenvoudig te gebruiken zijn – en complexe problemen oplossen."
```

## Maintenance

- **Review translations** with native speakers when possible
- **Test UI layout** with different text lengths
- **Keep translations in sync** when content changes
- **Document translation decisions** for complex content